#
# ENGINE_PIN — the exact vouchfx engine commit this samples repo builds against.
#
# What it pins
# ------------
# The first line is a full 40-character commit SHA on
# https://github.com/tomas-rampas/vouchfx. scripts/bootstrap.{ps1,sh} shallow-fetch
# exactly this commit into .vouchfx-src/ and build the engine CLI
# (src/Cli/Vouchfx.Cli/Vouchfx.Cli.csproj) from source at that revision.
#
# A full SHA is required, not a short SHA or a branch/tag name: a shallow
# `git fetch --depth 1 origin <ref>` only accepts a full SHA or a ref that the
# remote advertises: a short SHA is silently rejected by most git servers'
# shallow-fetch machinery, and pinning a moving branch name (e.g. "main")
# would defeat the point of a pin — reproducible builds and an auditable,
# reviewable upgrade step.
#
# If the SHA above is ever the all-zeros placeholder, bootstrap will
# refuse to run against it. The orchestrator stamps the real engine SHA here
# as part of standing this repository up; from then on, advancing the pin is
# a deliberate, reviewed action (see below).
#
# When to advance it
# -------------------
# Bump this SHA when:
#   - a new vouchfx engine release or milestone lands that the samples should
#     track (e.g. a new Sprint/Milestone merges to the engine's main branch);
#   - a sample needs an engine fix or a new provider that only exists past
#     the current pin;
#   - the engine's v1.x SDK contract freeze advances and this repo should
#     validate against the new baseline.
#
# NOTE: the ledger-jsonrpc sample's custom runner ProjectReferences engine-
# internal paths under .vouchfx-src/ and keeps a packages.lock.json — an
# advance that reorganises the engine tree breaks its build (step 3's
# run-sample all re-run catches this), and the lock file may need
# regeneration (dotnet restore) after the advance.
#
# How to advance it
# ------------------
#   0. EASIEST: scripts/bump-engine-pin.{sh,ps1} <tag-or-branch-or-sha> ["reason"]
#      resolves a tag/branch to its full commit SHA (no local clone needed)
#      and rewrites this file's first line + a new dated "Pin history" entry
#      for you — steps 1-2 below, done correctly in one command. It does NOT
#      do steps 3-4; those remain a deliberate, reviewed action.
#
#      If doing it by hand instead, two easy ways to find the commit SHA for
#      a given tag/release WITHOUT cloning:
#        - GitHub: open the release/tag page (e.g.
#          github.com/tomas-rampas/vouchfx/releases/tag/v1.0.0-alpha.5) and
#          click the short-SHA link under the tag name to reach the full SHA.
#        - `git ls-remote --tags https://github.com/tomas-rampas/vouchfx <tag>`
#          — GOTCHA: for an ANNOTATED tag (this project's tags are annotated)
#          this prints TWO lines: `refs/tags/<tag>` (the tag OBJECT's own
#          SHA) and `refs/tags/<tag>^{}` (the COMMIT it points at, "peeled").
#          Always take the `^{}` line — ENGINE_PIN must hold the commit SHA,
#          never the tag object's SHA. (`gh api repos/tomas-rampas/vouchfx/commits/<tag>
#          --jq .sha` sidesteps this entirely by resolving straight to the
#          commit.) scripts/bump-engine-pin.* does this peeling for you.
#
#   1. Pick the new engine commit (a merge commit on tomas-rampas/vouchfx main
#      is usually the right choice — record its full 40-char SHA, not a
#      branch name).
#   2. Replace the SHA on the first line of this file with the new one.
#   3. Delete any local .vouchfx-src/ checkout (scripts/bootstrap.* will
#      re-fetch it) and re-run `scripts/run-sample.* all` to confirm every
#      sample still passes against the new pin.
#   4. Open a PR with just the pin bump (plus any sample changes the new
#      engine revision requires) so the change is reviewable in isolation.
#
# Role decision (2026-07-08): the vouchfx engine published v1.0.0-alpha
# pre-releases to NuGet.org and GitHub. This file's role *deliberately* remains
# "commit to build from source" — the packaged CLI embeds an absolute DCP
# binary path resolved at NuGet-cache-time, so it only runs on machines with
# a matching aspire.hosting.orchestration version already installed. Building
# from source here ensures every CI run is self-sufficient and reproducible.
# Revisit this decision at v1.0.0 GA when DCP portability is confirmed stable.
#
